In Java, the `==` operator is used to compare references, not the contents of the objects being referenced. When you use `==` to compare strings, you are actually comparing the references, not the string values. This is why it might not work as expected when you expect it to compare the string contents.

On the other hand, the `.equals()` method is used to compare the actual contents of the objects, including the string values. This is why using `.equals()` fixed your bug.

### When to Use `==` and When to Use `.equals()`

- **Use `==` to compare references:**
  - When you want to check if two variables refer to the same object.
  - Example:
    ```java
    String str1 = "Hello";
    String str2 = str1;
    if (str1 == str2) {
        System.out.println("str1 and str2 refer to the same object");
    }
    ```

- **Use `.equals()` to compare the contents of objects:**
  - When you want to check if two objects have the same value, regardless of whether they refer to the same object.
  - Example:
    ```java
